li.p:
The slope-intercept form, y = mx + b, is just a special case of the point-slope formula. If the given point (x_1, y_1) happens to be the y-intercept (0, b), then the point-slope formula reduces to the familiar form:

        y\amp =y_1+m(x-x_1) \amp\amp\glert{\text{Substitute } b \text{ for } y_1 \text{ and 0 for } x_1.}

        y\amp = b + m(x-0) \amp\amp \glert{\text{Simplify.}}

        y\amp = mx + b

We can use the (shorter) slope-intercept form if we are lucky enough to know the y-intercept of the line.

