solution.p:
Algebraically, we solve the equation as follows. 


First, we isolate the variable.  We add 7 to both sides, then multiply by 2, yielding ~x^2=30.

Because x is squared in this equation, we perform the opposite operation, or take square roots, in order to solve for x. 
                     x^2 \amp = 30  \amp \amp \glert{\text{Take square roots of both sides.}} x \amp = \pm \sqrt{30} \amp \amp \glert{\text{Remember that every positive number}}
                          \amp   \amp \amp \glert{\text{has two square roots.}}



We use a calculator to find that \sqrt{30} is approximately 5.477, or about 5.5, as we saw on the graph.

