section.subsection:
Complex Numbers
Not all quadratic equations have solutions that are real numbers.  For example, when we try to solve the equation ~x^2+4=0,~, we find
    x^2 \amp =-4x \amp = \pm \sqrt{-4}
Although square roots of negative numbers such as \sqrt{-4}  are not real numbers, they occur frequently in mathematics and its applications.  Mathematicians in the sixteenth century gave them the name imaginary numbers, which reflected the mistrust with which they were viewed at the time.  Today, however, such numbers are well understood and are used routinely by scientists and engineers.
To help us work with imaginary numbers, we define a new number, i, the imaginary unit, whose square is -1. Imaginary Unit
\blert{i = \sqrt{-1}}~~~~\text{or}~~~~\blert{i^2=-1}
 With this new number we define the principal square root of any negative real number as follows.Imaginary Numbers
If ~a \ge 0,
    \blert{\sqrt{-a} = \sqrt{-1}\sqrt{a} = i\sqrt{a}}
Thus, the square root of any negative real number can be written as the product of a real number and i.  Every negative real number has two imaginary square roots.  For example, the square roots of -9 are 3i and -3i.  You can verify that
    (3i)^2=9i^2=9(-1)=-9~~~\text{and}~~~(-3i)^2=(-3)^2i^2=9(-1)=-9


\sqrt{-4} \amp = \sqrt{-1}\sqrt{4} \amp = i \sqrt{4} = 2i

\sqrt{-3} \amp = \sqrt{-1}\sqrt{3} \amp = i \sqrt{3} Practice 3
Simplify. 
-\sqrt{-36}
(5i)^2
-6i
-25
The solutions of many quadratic equations involve imaginary numbers.

            Solve ~~2x^2-x+2 = 0.


            For this equation, a=\alert{2}, b=\alert{-1}, and c=\alert{2}. We substitute these values into the quadratic formula to obtain

                    x=\frac{ -(\alert{-1}) \pm \sqrt{ (\alert{-1})^2 - 4(\alert{2}) (\alert{2})} } { 2(\alert{2}) } = \frac{1 \pm \sqrt{-15} } {4}

            We write the solutions as 

                    \frac{1 \pm i\sqrt{15}}{4} \qquad \text{or} \qquad \frac{1}{4} \pm \frac{\sqrt{15}}{4}

            Because the solutions are not real numbers, the graph of 

                y=2x^2-x+2

            has no x-intercepts, as shown below.parabola no x-intercepts

