li.p:
We set y=\alert{0} and solve the resulting equation to find the x-intercepts.

         \dfrac{(x+2)^2}{16} + \dfrac{(\alert{0}-1)^2}{5} \amp = 1 \amp\amp \glert{\text{Subtract}~ \dfrac{1}{5}~ \text{from both sides.}}

        \dfrac{(x+2)^2}{16} \amp = \dfrac{4}{5} \amp\amp \glert{\text{Multiply both sides by 16.}}

        (x+2)^2 \amp = \dfrac{64}{5} \amp\amp \glert{\text{Extract roots.}}

         x+2 \amp = \pm \sqrt{\dfrac{64}{5}}

        x \amp = -2 \pm \dfrac{8\sqrt{5}}{5}

The x-intercepts are \left(-2 \pm \dfrac{8\sqrt{5}}{5}, 0\right) or approximately (1.6,0) and (-5.6,0). We set x=\alert{0} to find the y-intercepts.

        \dfrac{(\alert{0}+2)^2}{16} + \dfrac{(y-1)^2}{5} \amp = 1 \amp\amp \glert{\text{Subtract}~ \dfrac{1}{4}~ \text{from both sides.}}

        \dfrac{(y-1)^2}{5} \amp = \dfrac{3}{4} \amp\amp \glert{\text{Multiply both sides by 5.}}

        (y-1)^2 \amp = \dfrac{15}{4} \amp\amp \glert{\text{Extract roots.}}

        y-1 \amp = \pm \sqrt{\dfrac{15}{4}}

        y \amp = 1 \pm \dfrac{\sqrt{15}}{2}

